# Org Skill Harness MVP Spec

## Executive Summary

An Org Skill Harness generates, verifies, and improves Agent Skills across selected repositories, turning repeated team workflows into portable, tested operating knowledge.

The MVP focuses on one wedge: repo onboarding into reusable skills for AI-heavy software teams of 2-20 people. The harness does not replace OpenClaw, Codex, Claude Code, Cursor, or other agent runtimes. It wraps existing agents through adapters and owns the skill lifecycle around them:

```text
discover -> distill -> approve -> verify -> cache -> use -> trace -> improve
```

Positioning:

> OpenClaw gives you agents and skills; this harness turns your team's repeated agent work into verified, repo-local and org-level Agent Skills that improve over time.

Sharper product promise:

> Stop rediscovering your repos. Generate tested Agent Skills from real agent traces.

## Problem

AI-heavy teams repeatedly spend agent context and human attention rediscovering the same facts:

- how a repo is structured
- which commands build, test, lint, migrate, and deploy
- which files implement important product concepts
- which conventions and failure modes matter
- which org standards apply to a code change
- which review, release, or debugging procedures should be followed

Current agents can use instructions, skills, memory, and repo context, but teams still lack a disciplined lifecycle for converting repeated agent work into small, portable, verified skills.

The market gap is not "another agent runtime." The gap is a harness that turns real work into durable operating knowledge.

## Target User

Primary user:

- AI-heavy software teams of 2-20 people
- already using Codex, Claude Code, OpenClaw, Cursor, custom agents, or agentic scripts
- managing multiple repos, but only some are relevant to agent workflows
- willing to keep skill artifacts in Git

Initial buyer/user profile:

- founder-engineer
- staff engineer
- platform engineer
- engineering lead
- AI tooling owner

## MVP Wedge

The MVP owns repo onboarding into reusable skills.

First successful outcome:

1. A user selects one or more repos to cover.
2. The harness explores selected repos.
3. The harness generates compact Agent Skills, resolver rules, and onboarding evals.
4. The user reviews and approves the generated pack.
5. The harness replays held-out onboarding tasks with and without the skill pack.
6. The user sees measurable improvement in repo-task correctness or reduced rediscovery cost.

Future workflows stay on the shelf:

1. PR/review workflow
2. release readiness
3. dependency upgrade campaign
4. bug/customer investigation
5. incident response
6. harness optimization lab

## Why This Is Different

Current offerings generally operate at one of these layers:

- Agent runtimes run sessions and tools.
- Skill systems package reusable instructions.
- Memory/RAG systems retrieve prior context.
- Repo instructions tell an agent what to remember.

The Org Skill Harness owns the skill lifecycle:

- generates skills from real repo/org exploration
- keeps skills small and progressive
- follows the Agent Skills specification
- routes skills using deterministic repo signals where possible
- verifies skills against held-out onboarding tasks
- proposes improvements from traces and corrections
- separates org-level skills from repo-specific skills
- covers only user-selected repos
- caches skills by pinned commit for reproducibility

The durable artifact is not a chat transcript. It is a versioned, reviewed, evaluated org skill pack.

## MVP Scope

In scope:

- CLI-first product
- central org skills repo as source of truth
- selected repo registration
- one or more covered repos
- repo onboarding workflow
- Agent Skills-compliant skill generation
- resolver generation
- lightweight eval generation and replay
- proposal-first learning
- adapter contract for existing agents
- one reference local adapter
- pinned local cache in selected repos

Out of scope:

- hosted dashboard
- full custom agent runtime
- fully autonomous self-improvement
- automatic mutation of accepted skills
- enterprise governance
- deep recursive multi-agent swarms
- org-wide repo crawling without explicit selection
- skill marketplace
- general-purpose workflow automation across every domain

## Product Category

Category:

> Org Skill Harness

Definition:

> An Org Skill Harness generates, verifies, and improves Agent Skills across selected repositories, turning repeated team workflows into portable, tested operating knowledge.

The product starts with selected repos, not full-org ingestion. Users choose which repositories the harness covers because some repos in an org may not be relevant.

## Core Concepts

### Org Skills

Org skills encode how the team works across repos.

MVP org skill families:

- Engineering standards: code review standard, testing philosophy, migration policy, security expectations.
- Cross-repo workflows: release readiness, incident debugging, dependency upgrades, feature rollout.
- Shared domain/context: product concepts, architecture glossary, business rules, compliance constraints.

### Repo Skills

Repo skills encode how a specific codebase works.

Examples:

- API architecture
- build-test-debug procedure
- database migration workflow
- frontend component conventions
- common failure modes

### Resolvers

Resolvers are deterministic routing hints. Agent Skills descriptions remain the portable baseline; `resolvers.yml` adds repo-specific routing.

Resolvers answer:

- when should a skill be loaded?
- which references should be suggested?
- which evals are required?
- which org skills apply to a repo task?

### Evals

Evals prove that the skill pack improves repo-specific performance.

The MVP uses lightweight held-out task replay, not heavyweight benchmark automation.

### Traces

Traces record what happened during exploration, evals, and skill use.

They are the substrate for future improvement proposals.

## Source of Truth

The source of truth is a central org skills repo.

Example:

```text
org-agent-skills/
  harness.yml
  org/
    skills/
      code-review-standard/
        SKILL.md
        references/
      release-policy/
        SKILL.md
      incident-debugging/
        SKILL.md
    resolvers.yml
  repos/
    api-service/
      skills/
        api-architecture/
          SKILL.md
          references/
        build-test-debug/
          SKILL.md
          scripts/
          references/
      evals/
        onboarding.yml
      resolvers.yml
    web-app/
      skills/
      evals/
      resolvers.yml
  proposals/
  traces/
    api-service/
    web-app/
```

Selected code repos contain only a lightweight pointer:

```yaml
# .agent-harness.yml
org_skill_pack: git@github.com:acme/org-agent-skills.git
repo_id: api-service
pack_ref: 8f3c1ab
```

Why central source of truth:

- versioned
- reviewable
- portable
- compatible with Git workflows
- avoids hosted-service dependency
- prevents skill drift across app repos

## Selected Repo Coverage

Repo coverage is explicit and user-chosen.

Example commands:

```bash
harness org init
harness repo add ../api-service --purpose "Core backend API and auth"
harness repo add ../web-app --purpose "Customer-facing React app"
harness repo skip ../infra-legacy --reason "Not relevant to agent workflows"
```

