# Org Skill Harness User Guide

This guide shows the normal interactive command a user runs when setting up the harness for an organization, a GitHub profile, or a small set of local repositories.

The harness creates a central `org-agent-skills/` directory. That directory is the source of truth for generated repo knowledge, human approvals, eval reports, exports, traces, and improvement proposals.

## Install / Run From Source

From this repository:

```bash
cd /Users/alexmetelli/source/orgs-ai-harness
export PYTHONPATH="$PWD/src"
```

Until the package is installed as a console script, run commands as:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness <command>
```

If installed, replace `python3 -m orgs_ai_harness` with `harness`.

## First-Time Interactive Setup

Most users should start with one command:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness setup https://github.com/ametel01
```

The setup wizard walks through the full flow interactively:

- infers or asks for the org name
- creates `org-agent-skills/` if it does not exist
- fetches visible GitHub repositories with `gh repo list`
- lets you select repositories with checkboxes
- asks whether to clone selected repositories locally
- validates the org skill pack
- asks whether to generate global org skills, project-specific repo skills, both, or neither
- asks which LLM should generate project-specific skills: Codex CLI or Claude Code
- asks whether generated skills should be installed for Codex only, Claude Code only, or both
- optionally shows review output and asks whether to approve generated project skills
- optionally runs development eval replay
- optionally refreshes repo-local caches and exports approved skills
- optionally explains the final repo state

For local-only setup, run:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness setup local
```

The local wizard asks for the org name, local repo paths, repo purpose/owner metadata, and whether generated skills should be global, project-specific, both, or skipped.
Project-specific skills are generated by the selected LLM from `local-docs/SINGLE_REPO_SKILL_BUILD.md`. Org-level shared-practice skills are generated from `local-docs/ORG_LEVEL_SKILL_BUILD.md`.

Generated skills are intentionally small and specialized. Metadata is treated as routing-critical: each `SKILL.md` description should let the agent decide whether to load that skill without pulling broad context.

Install locations:

- Codex repo-level skills: `.agents/skills/` inside the cloned repo
- Claude Code repo-level skills: `.claude/skills/` inside the cloned repo
- Codex global org skills: `~/.agents/skills/`
- Claude Code global org skills: `~/.claude/skills/`

Org-level LLM generation writes first into `org-agent-skills/org/llm-output/`, validates the generated skill set, then installs it into `~/.agents/skills/`, `~/.claude/skills/`, or both. The full transcript is written to `org-agent-skills/org/org-level-skill-generation.log`, and the CLI prints concise progress while the selected LLM is working.

The generated skill shape follows the richer pattern used by `/Users/alexmetelli/source/aztec-skills`: frontmatter in `SKILL.md`, concise procedural instructions in the main file, and deeper material in reference files.

## Manual Org Setup

Create a workspace for your org skill pack with an explicit name:

```bash
mkdir acme-agent-harness
cd acme-agent-harness
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness org init --name acme
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness validate
```

Or paste a GitHub org/profile URL and let the harness infer the pack name:

```bash
mkdir ametel01-agent-harness
cd ametel01-agent-harness
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo discover https://github.com/ametel01
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness validate
```

When no org pack exists yet, `repo discover <github-url>` initializes `org-agent-skills/` with the inferred GitHub owner name, then continues into repository discovery.

This creates:

```text
org-agent-skills/
  harness.yml
  org/
    resolvers.yml
    skills/
  repos/
  proposals/
  trace-summaries/
```

Use this directory as the Git-friendly source of truth. Commit it to whatever repo will hold your organization’s agent skill pack.

If an org pack already exists locally, attach to it instead:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness org init --repo ../org-agent-skills
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness validate
```

If the org pack exists only as a remote Git URL, clone it first, then attach to the local clone.

## Add Repositories Manually

Use manual registration when you already know which repos should be covered.

Local repo:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo add ../api-service \
  --purpose "Core backend API" \
  --owner platform
```

Remote repo URL without a local checkout:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo add git@github.com:acme/web-app.git \
  --purpose "Customer web app" \
  --owner product
```

External dependency reference:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo add git@github.com:vendor/sdk.git --external
```

List and validate coverage:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo list
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness validate
```

Only active selected repos can be onboarded. External repos are visible as references, but are not treated as selected coverage.

## Discover Repositories From GitHub

GitHub discovery uses your locally authenticated `gh` CLI.

Check auth first:

```bash
gh auth status
```

Paste a GitHub organization or profile URL and select repos interactively:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo discover https://github.com/ametel01
```

The harness fetches visible repos with `gh repo list` and opens a checkbox selector in an interactive terminal. Use `Up`/`Down` or `j`/`k` to move, `Space` to select repositories, `a` to toggle all, `Enter` to confirm, and `q` to cancel.

If you run this from a directory without an org pack, the harness creates `org-agent-skills/` first and uses the pasted GitHub owner as `org.name`.
After selected repos are registered, an interactive `repo discover` continues into the same setup steps as `setup`: clone prompt, validation, global/project-specific skill generation choice, optional approval, optional development eval replay, optional cache/export, and optional explain output.
If a selected repo already exists in the chosen clone directory, the harness prints a warning, skips that clone, records the existing directory as the repo local path, and continues cloning the remaining repos.

The same command can run non-interactively with `--select`:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo discover https://github.com/ametel01 \
  --select cli-tools,docs-site
```

You can still use explicit org/user flags when preferred.

Discover from a GitHub organization:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo discover \
  --github-org acme \
  --select api-service,web-app
```

Discover from a GitHub user/profile:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo discover \
  --github-user alexmetelli \
  --select cli-tools,docs-site
```

Clone selected repos while registering them:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo discover https://github.com/acme \
  --select api-service,web-app \
  --clone \
  --clone-dir ./covered-repos
```

Archived repos and forks are hidden by default. Include them explicitly:

```bash
python3 -m orgs_ai_harness repo discover \
  --github-org acme \
  --include-archived \
  --include-forks \
  --select old-tool,forked-sdk
```

Discovery never adds every repo automatically. A repo is written to `harness.yml` only when selected with `--select`.

